Basically Timeouts control how long a system waits at different stages of a request lifecycle.
1. Connection Timeout  : Time allowed to establish a connection between client and server.

2. Read Request Timeout (Read Timeout) :
> Time to receive data AFTER connection is established
> Connection is successful, but server is slow to send response.
> Generally happen at the : Slow database query , Heavy processing , Server overload

3. Wait Timeout (Idle Timeout)
> How long a connection can stay idle (no activity) before closing.
> If no query is executed for 10 sec → connection closed
> we see this in the Important in DB connection pools

4. Usage Timeout (Execution Timeout) :
> Maximum time allowed to execute a task/process in an api call.
> we generally get this at the : Long loops, CPU-heavy tasks, Prevent blocking.

5. Response Timeout :
>  Total time allowed for full response cycle
> This includes , connections + processing + sending response|
> If request not completed in specified time we get the errors.

6. Cancelling a Request :
> Force stop a request before it completes
> Request is manually cancelled


ProcessExit Codes :

> process.exit() is a function in Node.js that stops your program immediately.
Syntax: process.exit(code)

process → global object in Node.js
exit() → tells Node: "stop execution NOW"


Here : The code is called an exit code , That number is called an exit code.



# Process.exit(0)
> Means: Success / Normal exit
> This is used When Task Completed successfully. And No errors.

# Process.exit(1)
> Means: Failure / Error happened
> This is used, when unexpected errors, validation failed, Crash Situation.


Note : We can not randloly use the numbers, The valid range is 0–255 (standard OS exit codes)


> process.exit(), This is very powerfull, It can 
❌ Stops event loop immediately
❌ Cancels pending async tasks
❌ Can drop requests (Express, Socket.IO)



